<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-071-102 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 460 404</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Object-Oriented Programming  Sept 1991 v4 n5 p56(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Tools for commercial applications.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Butterworth, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>One of the main goals of the object-oriented programming communityis to extend to use of this programming model into the area ofcommercial applications development.andP;  Object-oriented programming(OOP) has mostly been used for research projects because it isdifficult to learn and has not been embraced by many commercialdevelopers, who are busy learning to use other new technologies.andO;But OOP programmers can look at the successful commercialacceptance of another technology, relational data base management(RDBMS), in order to recognize elements that can speed use andacceptance.andP;  RDBMS products generally support rapid development ofthe user interface with a screen designer that directlymanipulates a window or screen image.andP;  High-level languageconstructs are another popular element, supplying the programmerwith menus of activities from which to select operations.andP;  Thebetter RDBMS systems support the inclusion of procedures from moretraditional application languages for certain programming tasks.andO;Tool integration, configuration management facilities, andmultiuser development support are other characteristics that canmake RDBMS products commercially appealing.andP;  OOP must providesimilar tools for commercial programmers in order to becomesuccessful in this arena.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Object-Oriented ProgrammingApplications ProgrammingRelational DBMSSoftware DesignProgram Development SoftwareData Base Management Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>